 reuptake inhibition","Dopamine D2 receptor antagonism","Muscarinic receptor agonism","Gamma-aminobutyric acid enhancement"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFirst-generation antipsychotics are characterised by their strong\u003Cstrong\u003E dopamine D2 receptor antagonism\u003C/strong\u003E, which is responsible for both their therapeutic effects and many of their side effects. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThey do not typically exhibit \u003Cstrong\u003Eselective serotonin reuptake inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Enoradrenaline reuptake inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E, which are properties of antidepressant medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGamma-aminobutyric acid enhancement\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of benzodiazepines and related drugs. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscarinic receptor agonism\u003C/strong\u003E is not a property of first-generation antipsychotics; in fact, many have antimuscarinic effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe strong D2 receptor blockade leads to reduction in positive psychotic symptoms but can also cause extrapyramidal side effects, elevated prolactin levels, and tardive dyskinesia. Examples include haloperidol and chlorpromazine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First-generation antipsychotics primarily work by blocking dopamine D2 receptors.","Common side effects of first-generation antipsychotics include extrapyramidal symptoms, hyperprolactinaemia, and sedation.","One example of a first-generation antipsychotic with strong D2 receptor blockade is haloperidol."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang 